[[Image:OsB2structure.JPG|right|thumb|200 px|Structure of [[orthorombic]] RuB<sub>2</sub>. Green atoms are Ru, pink - boron]] '''Ruthenium borides''' are compounds of [[ruthenium]] and [[boron]]. Their most remarkable property is potentially high hardness. [[Vickers hardness test|Vickers hardness]] H<sub>V</sub> = 50 GPa was reported for thin films composed of RuB<sub>2</sub> and Ru<sub>2</sub>B<sub>3</sub> phases.<ref>J.V. Rau et al. "Deposition and characterization of superhard biphasic ruthenium boride films" [https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.actamat.2008.10.009 Acta Materialia 57 (2009) 673]</ref> This value is significantly higher than those of bulk RuB<sub>2</sub> or Ru<sub>2</sub>B<sub>3</sub>, but it has to be confirmed independently, as measurements on superhard materials are intrinsically difficult. For example, note that the initial report on extreme hardness of related material [[rhenium diboride]]<ref name="Chung">{{cite journal|last=Chung|first=Hsiu-Ying|date=April 20, 2007|title=Synthesis of Ultra-Incompressible Superhard Rhenium Diboride at Ambient Pressure|journal=Science|volume=316|issue=5823|pages=436–9|doi=10.1126/science.1139322|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/abstract/316/5823/436|pmid=17446399|bibcode = 2007Sci...316..436C |display-authors=etal}}</ref> was probably too optimistic.<ref>J. Qin et al. "Is Rhenium Diboride a Superhard Material?" [http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/121453064/abstract Adv. Mater. 20 (2008) 4780]</ref>
==Structure== Ruthenium diboride was first thought to have a hexagonal structure,<ref>C. P. Kempter and R. J. Fries "Crystallography of the Ru-B and Os-B Systems" [http://link.aip.org/link/?JCPSA6/34/1994/1 J. Chem. Phys. 34, 1994 (1961)]</ref> as in [[rhenium diboride]], but it was later tentatively determined to possess an [[orthorhombic]] structure.<ref>R. B. Roof, Jr. and C. P. Kempter "New Orthorhombic Phase in the Ru-B and Os-B Systems" [http://link.aip.org/link/?JCPSA6/37/1473/1 J. Chem. Phys. 37, 1473 (1962)]</ref>
